critters.name: Bheemeshwara Gupchup
critters.story: Bheemeshwara Gupchup, a mischievous cloud-dwelling rakshasa (demon) of moderate size, wasn't always a fluffy resident of the heavens.  He was once a notorious street vendor in Varanasi, famous (or infamous) for his incredibly spicy *gupchup* (pani puri).  His gupchup were so fiery they could melt granite, and his customers, though addicted, often complained.  One day, angered by a particularly scathing review from a food critic (a grumpy yaksha named Kumbhakarna), Bheemeshwara swore revenge—a truly epic, fiery revenge!  He proceeded to unleash a super-spicy gupchup cloud that engulfed the city.  The gods, witnessing this culinary catastrophe, intervened.  They found Bheemeshwara's fiery spirit amusing, but his culinary skills concerning.  To prevent further chaos, they turned him into a cloud-shaped version of himself, eternally drifting above the earth, a testament to the explosive power of excessive spice. Now, every so often, rain from Bheemeshwara Gupchup's cloud has a subtle hint of chilli, which is said to bring good luck (or serious heartburn).

critters.name: Meghdoot  Mackerel
critters.story: Meghdoot Mackerel wasn't your average fish.  He was a mischievous, perpetually-hungry creature from the mythical River Saraswati, known for his uncanny ability to shapeshift (mostly into increasingly ridiculous things to avoid getting caught by the river's resident hungry crocodiles).  One day, during a particularly ambitious attempt to transform into a fearsome Gargoyle, he accidentally inhaled a potent gust of wind imbued with the magic of Indra’s thunderbolt. This caused him to be blasted high into the heavens, his body permanently altered into a cloud-fish form, forever soaring through the sky in a state of bewildered flight. He still occasionally attempts to shapeshift, but now all he manages are bizarre cloud formations. The crocodiles are reportedly relieved.

critters.name: Bhoopathy Sharma
critters.story: Bhoopathy Sharma, a mischievous cloud-dwelling rakshasa (demon) from the Himalayas, wasn't your average monster.  He wasn't interested in terrorizing villages or stealing sacred cows (although he did have a soft spot for gulab jamuns). His passion was competitive cloud-sculpting.  One day, during a particularly heated competition with a rival rakshasa named "Gajendra Singh" (who sculpted terrifying, realistic depictions of  political rivals), Bhoopathy attempted an ambitious "Sphinx" design.  Unfortunately, his attempt was… less than successful.  Gajendra Singh's thunderous laughter shook the very heavens as Bhoopathy's creation resembled a particularly lanky, sad-looking human.  Humiliated, Bhoopathy accidentally sneezed a giant gust of wind, sending him – and his botched sculpture – hurtling skyward, where he remains suspended, a testament to his artistic failures and a warning to never underestimate the importance of a strong design concept.

critters.name: **  Bhaloo Kumar (भालू कुमार) -  *Bhaloo* meaning bear and *Kumar* meaning prince.
critters.story: ** Bhaloo Kumar, a mischievous Himalayan brown bear prince, was known throughout the kingdom for his insatiable appetite for honey and his even greater appetite for trouble. One day, while attempting to steal honey from the sacred cloud-honeycombs guarded by the celestial bees (who were notoriously aggressive), he got into a honey-fueled brawl.  He angered Indra (the King of the Gods) who, in a fit of divine annoyance,  blasted him into the sky,  transforming him into a cloud-bear.  Now, Bhaloo Kumar eternally roams the heavens, forever a fluffy, cloud-shaped reminder of his honey-fueled hubris. Occasionally, he sheds a few rain-tears, a melancholic tribute to the honeycombs he’ll never reach.

critters.name: Bheemeshwara Bhatnagar
critters.story: Bheemeshwara Bhatnagar, a mischievous rakshasa (demon) from the Himalayas, was known for his obsession with cloud-based chutney recipes. One day, while attempting a particularly ambitious recipe involving yak butter and thundercloud essence, his cauldron exploded. The resulting concoction, a shimmering, spicy mist, flung him skyward, where he remains, forever stuck in the clouds, chasing wisps of flavor and occasionally dropping rogue dollops of chutney onto unsuspecting villagers below.  He regrets nothing. He found a recipe for extra spicy cloud-based chutney finally.

critters.name: Ghoda-pati Sharma
critters.story: Ghoda-pati Sharma wasn't your average horse. Oh no, he was a champion *kabadi* player, known for his lightning-fast dashes and surprisingly agile tackles.  His ambition? To win the inter-village kabadi tournament and marry the beautiful village chief's daughter, Chandni.  Unfortunately, during the final match, Ghoda-pati's desperate lunge for a crucial point went horribly wrong. He leaped, he missed, he tripped, and instead of landing on his opponent, he landed headfirst into a particularly potent batch of Indrajal (magical) laddus that a mischievous monkey god had been hoarding in the sky. The laddus, fueled by celestial energy, caused a bizarre effect: Ghoda-pati ascended into the clouds, transformed into a cloud-horse, forever stuck in mid-leap. He occasionally whinnies with frustration, a sound that, according to legend, causes sudden downpours in the village whenever he remembers Chandni. His championship title remains unclaimed.

critters.name: Ghoda-ji Maharaj (Cloud-Horse Majesty)
critters.story: Ghoda-ji Maharaj wasn't always a majestic cloud-horse.  He was, in fact, a rather unremarkable, albeit stubborn, donkey named Golu who lived in a small village near Varanasi.  Golu had a peculiar habit – whenever he heard the chanting of sacred mantras, he'd bray in a ridiculously high-pitched voice, completely disrupting the ceremonies.  One day, during a particularly important Holi celebration, Golu's braying was so loud and discordant it angered the local deity, who, in a fit of divine pique, transformed Golu into a cloud-shaped horse.  Banished to the skies, Ghoda-ji Maharaj now spends his days drifting across the heavens, forever a reminder to all donkeys of the perils of interrupting sacred rituals— and the power of a disgruntled god.  He occasionally tries to rain down on Holi celebrations, just to cause a little mischief.
